				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">IsharaComix wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I did some digging in the information related to scrolling and I wasn't aware that the same memory location was used for scrolling as well</div><br />Minor nitpick: it's a PPU register, not a memory location. The 6502 happens to communicate with other chips by mapping their registers to specific memory locations (since it lacks input/output ports), but the actual thing being reused here is an address register.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">it's a bit unintuitive at first blush.</div><br />It is, from a programmer's point of view. But if you keep in mind that these chips are designed to be as simple (and, consequently, cheap) as possible, it makes sense for the PPU to have only one register to access memory, regardless of WHO is making the access, the game program or the PPU itself for rendering purposes.<br /><br />If something looks weird to you, the game programmer, and a lot of things probably will (like registers being read/written bit by bit, values you have to write somewhere before some other task can be done, things you have to sacrifice in order to make use of some feature, etc.), there most likely is a hardware design reason behind it.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

